2.2 Data Extraction and Engineering

2.2.1 Creating Outcome Variable: performance

The outcome variable of this analysis is whether a school is identified as low-performing based on NC school performance grade system.

# List of low-performing schools in AY 2021-2022
lp_2022 <- src_data_list[["rcd_acc_lowperf.xlsx"]] |> 
  # Non-charter public schools in AY 2021-2022
  filter(year == 2022,
         # Charter schools and district code contain letters
         !grepl("[a-zA-Z]", agency_code)) |> 
  # Transforming the outcome varaible from Y/N to Low/High
  mutate(performance = ifelse(lp_school == "Y", "Low", "High")) |>
  # Keeping needed varaibles 
  select(agency_code, performance) 

# List of low-performing schools in AY 2022-2023
lp_2023 <- src_data_list[["rcd_acc_lowperf.xlsx"]] |> 
  # Non-charter public schools in AY 2022-2023
  filter(year == 2023,
         # Charter schools and district code contain letters
         !grepl("[a-zA-Z]", agency_code)) |> 
  # Transforming the outcome varaible from Y/N to Low/High
  mutate(performance = ifelse(lp_school == "Y", "Low", "High")) |>
  # Keeping needed variables 
  select(agency_code, performance)

3.2 Class Distribution (SMOTE)

Ensuring a balanced distribution across classes is critical for the performance of classification models because imbalanced datasets can lead to biased predictions. When one class significantly outnumbers the other(s), the model may become biased toward the majority class, leading to poor generalization on the minority class. So let’s check how the classes distribute in the current dataset.

# Checking the number and percentage of observation in each class 
class_distribution <- data_2022_cleaned |>
  # Number
  count(performance) |>
  # Percentage 
  mutate(percentage = n / sum(n))

Not too bad… but can be better. Let’s apply SMOTE to 2022 data. SMOTE (Synthetic Minority Oversampling Technique) is a widely used method to address this imbalance by oversampling the minority class. Instead of duplicating existing samples, SMOTE generates synthetic samples to increase diversity within the minority class. It works by identifying the minority class samples and selecting a random subset of their k-nearest neighbors in feature space. New synthetic samples are created by interpolating between these points, ensuring variability.

For example, a synthetic sample is calculated as:

\(\text{Synthetic Sample} = x_i + \delta \times (x_{nn} - x_i)\)

where \(x_i\)​ is a minority class sample, \(x_{nn}​\) is a randomly chosen nearest neighbor, and \(\delta\) is a random number between 0 and 1. These new samples are then added to the dataset, balancing the class distribution and improving the model’s ability to generalize.

Note: The following codes rely on the package called DMwR. It has been removed from CRAN, but it can be downloaded from github using by calling the following code: remotes::install_github("cran/DMwR")

set.seed(7749)
# Balancing the case by applying SMOTE 
data_2022_smote <- DMwR::SMOTE(performance ~ ., 
                         data = data_2022_cleaned, 
                         # Doubeling the number of low-performing schools 
                         perc.over = 100,  
                         # Keeping half of created cases as high-performing schools
                         perc.under = 200)

# Check the distribution 
class_distribution_SMOTE <- data_2022_smote |> 
  # Number
  count(performance) |>
  # Percentage 
  mutate(percentage = n / sum(n))

Let’s compare the class distribution before and after SMOTE through bar plot.

# Preparing data vis dataframe

4.3 ROC AUC

4.3.1 Calculating AUC

# Decision Tree
roc_dt <- roc(response = data_2023_cleaned$performance,
                 predictor = factor(dt_pred$prediction, ordered = TRUE))
## Setting levels: control = High, case = Low
## Warning in value[[3L]](cond): Ordered predictor converted to numeric vector.
## Threshold values will not correspond to values in predictor.
## Setting direction: controls < cases
# Logistic Regression
roc_logit <- roc(response = data_2023_cleaned$performance,
                 predictor = factor(logit_pred$prediction, ordered = TRUE))
## Setting levels: control = High, case = Low
## Warning in value[[3L]](cond): Ordered predictor converted to numeric vector.
## Threshold values will not correspond to values in predictor.
## Setting direction: controls < cases
# Random Forest 
roc_rf <- roc(response = data_2023_cleaned$performance,
    predictor = factor(rf_pred$prediction, ordered = TRUE))
## Setting levels: control = High, case = Low
## Warning in value[[3L]](cond): Ordered predictor converted to numeric vector.
## Threshold values will not correspond to values in predictor.
## Setting direction: controls < cases
# Creating a metric table
evaluation_metrics_all_models <- bind_rows(dt_cm_table, logit_cm_table, rf_cm_table) |>
  # Reshaping to wide format
  pivot_wider(names_from = Metric, values_from = Value) |>
  # Calculating false alarms rate 
  mutate(`1-Specificity` = 1 - Specificity) |>
  # Keeping metrics we want 
  select(Model, Sensitivity, Precision, `1-Specificity`) |>
  # Rounding the values
  mutate(Sensitivity = round(Sensitivity, 4),
         Precision = round(Precision, 4),
         `1-Specificity` = round(`1-Specificity`, 4))

# Creating a AUC table
auc_table <- data.frame(Model = c("Classification Tree",
                                  "Logistic Regression",
                                  "Random Forest"),
                        AUC = c(auc(roc_dt),
                                auc(roc_logit),
                                auc(roc_rf))) |>
  # Rounding the values
  mutate(AUC = round(AUC, 4))

# Merging the two tables
evaluation_table <- merge(evaluation_metrics_all_models, auc_table, by = "Model") |>
  # Ordering from largest to smallest
  arrange(desc(AUC))

4.3.2 Comparing AUC Values (Delong Test)

# Creating a list
roc_list <- list(roc_dt, roc_logit, roc_rf)
# Creating pairs for comparison 
pairs <- combn(seq_along(roc_list), 2, simplify = FALSE)
# Running delong test
delong_test <- lapply(pairs, function(pair) {
  roc.test(roc_list[[pair[1]]], roc_list[[pair[2]]], method = "delong")
})
# Confirming the order of tests
pairs

## [1] 1 2
## 
## [[2]]

## [[3]]
## [1] 2 3
# Creating a significance stats table for easier comparison
model1 <- c("Classification Tree", "Classification Tree", "Logistic Regression")
model2 <- c("Logistic Regression", "Random Forest", "Random Forest")

z_values <- sapply(delong_test, function(delong_test) round(delong_test$statistic, 3))
p_values <- sapply(delong_test, function(delong_test) ifelse(delong_test$p.value < 0.001, "<0.001", round(delong_test$p.value, 3)))

delong_table <- data.frame(Model1 = model1,
                           Model2 = model2,
                           Z = z_values,
                           p_value = p_values)

4.4 Importance of Variables

# Creating a table for variable importance in classification tree
var_impor_dt <- varImp(dt_fit2) |>
  # Converting rownames as column 
  rownames_to_column(var = "Variable") |>
  # Rename for clarity 
  rename(Importance = Overall)|>
  # Creating a column to signify the model
  mutate(Model = "Classification Tree")

# Getting the variable importance in logistic regression
var_impor_logit_object<- varImp(logit_fit)
# Calculate variable importance
var_impor_logit <- as.data.frame(var_impor_logit_object$importance) |>
  # Converting rownames as column 
  rownames_to_column(var = "Variable") |>
  # Rename for clarity 
  rename(Importance = Overall) |>
  # Creating a column to signify the model
  mutate(Model = "Logistic Regression")

var_impor_rf <- as.data.frame(importance(rf_fit2)) |>
  # Converting rownames as column 
  rownames_to_column(var = "Variable") |>
  # Keep only the relevant columns
  select(Variable, MeanDecreaseAccuracy, MeanDecreaseGini) |>
  # Pivot to long format
  pivot_longer(
    cols = c(MeanDecreaseAccuracy, MeanDecreaseGini),  
    names_to = "Model",      
    values_to = "Importance"        
  ) |>
  # Rename Model column values based on their original name
  mutate(Model = ifelse(Model == "MeanDecreaseAccuracy", 
                        "RF: Accuracy", 
                        "RF: Gini"))
# Combine the three data frames
var_impor_merged <- bind_rows(var_impor_dt, var_impor_logit, var_impor_rf)

# Normalize importance scores within each model
var_impor_normalized <- var_impor_merged |>
  group_by(Model) |>
  mutate(Normalized_Importance = (Importance - min(Importance)) / (max(Importance) - min(Importance))) |>
  ungroup()

# Extract variable order based on "Classification Tree"
reference_order <- var_impor_normalized |>
  filter(Model == "Classification Tree") |>
  arrange(Importance) |>
  pull(Variable)

# Reorder Variable column globally
var_impor_normalized <- var_impor_normalized |>
  mutate(Variable = factor(Variable, levels = reference_order))
# Create a heatmap
var_impor_heatmap <- ggplot(var_impor_normalized,
                            aes(x = Model, y = Variable, fill = Normalized_Importance)) +
  geom_tile(color = "white") +
  scale_fill_gradient(low = "lightblue",
                      high = "darkblue",
                      name = "Normalized\nImportance") +
  scale_x_discrete(
    labels = c(
      "Classification Tree" = "CT (Gini)",
      "Logistic Regression" = "LR (Abs Coeffi)",
      "RF: Accuracy" = "RF (Mean Accuracy)",
      "RF: Gini" = "RF (Mean Gini)"
    )
  ) +
  labs(
    title = "Percentage of Effective Teachers is the Most Important Variable across Three Models",
    x = "Model",
    y = "Variable",
    caption = "Classification Tree: How much a variable reduces impurity during splits
Logistic Regression: Derived from the absolute values of coefficients
Random Forest (Accuracy): The impact on model accuracy when a variable is removed
Rondom Forest (Gini): The variable's contribution to reducing node impurity across all splits"
  ) +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(
    axis.text.y = element_text(size = 10),
    plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 12, face = "bold"),

  )

spg_details <- src_data_list[["rcd_acc_spg2.xlsx"]] |>
  filter(year == "2022",
         subgroup == "ALL") |>
  select(agency_code, spg_grade, spg_score) 

# We need to merge the school performance data back to data_2022
data_2022_vis <- data_2022 |> 
  rownames_to_column(var = "agency_code")

# Merge the two datasets
teachers_vis <- left_join(data_2022_vis, spg_details, by = "agency_code") |>
  drop_na() |>
  select(agency_code, spg_grade, spg_score, pct_eff_teachers)

# Creating a boxplot to show the between class difference
eff_teachers_plot <- ggplot(teachers_vis, aes(x = spg_grade, y = pct_eff_teachers)) +
  geom_violin(fill = "#1E88E5", alpha = 0.8) +
  geom_boxplot(
    width = 0.1,
    color = "black",
    fill = "#E8E8E8",
    alpha = 0.7
  ) +
  stat_compare_means(comparisons = list(c("A", "B"), c("B", "C"), c("C", "D"), c("D", "F")), method = "t.test", label = "p.farmat") +
  scale_y_continuous(breaks = c(0, 25, 50, 75, 100), limits = c(0, 140)) +
  labs(x = "School Porformance Grade", 
       y = "Percentage of Effective Teachers",
       title = "Percentage of Effective Teachers in Schools by Performance Grades") +
  theme_minimal() +
  theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size = 14, face = "bold"))

# Displaying plot 
eff_teachers_plot

# Saving plot 
ggsave("eff_teachers_plot.png", eff_teachers_plot, height = 6, width = 8, dpi = 600)
